dataset.title: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities, Riparian Permanent Sample Plots 2003-current, Cedar River Municipal Watershed, King County, WA

abstract.para: The City of Seattleâ€™s Cedar River Municipal Watershed is managed to support and supply clean drinking water to 1.6 million people in the greater Seattle area. The watershed covers 91,000 acres, hosts a rich diversity of plants, animals, and habitats, and is owned by the City of Seattle. From 2003 to 2005, Seattle Public Utilities established 61 permanent sample plots in riparian habitats of the Cedar River Municipal Watershed.

31 of these plots (plot #s 1-31) were established in 2003 upstream of Chester Morse Lake, the drinking water reservoir for the City of Seattle. 30 additional plots (plot #s 32-61) were established in 2005 downstream of Chester Morse Lake. In 2012, 6 of the 61 total plots (plot #s 4, 11, 12, 27, 28, 29) were resampled and the sampling methods were simplified. Each sampling year had different surveyors.

The riparian permanent sample plots were limited to low gradient, moderately to unconfined reaches along the Cedar River and its tributaries because they typically show the most variability in riparian condition, stream-riparian interactions are greatest, and fish use is highest. Sites were randomly selected along these reaches, with two plots located at each site, one on each side of the stream. Sites were stratified into four stand types: deciduous dominated, mixed deciduous/conifer, conifer dominated in stem exclusion phase with little understory, and conifer dominated differentiated with well-developed understory, with at least five plots in each type. Selection of riparian plots for resampling in 2012 was designed to include plots in second and old growth forests and with medium and large stream sizes. Future resampling is expected to occur at an approximately ten-year interval. This data package will be updated after resampling efforts occur.

Each plot was measured for tree species and diameter, snag diameter and height, shrub species and cover, herb species and cover, sapling species and cover, percent canopy cover, and other species found in the plots but not previously recorded in the tree, shrub, and herb sampling.

description.para: Plots were limited to low gradient, moderately to unconfined reaches along chosen streams. Sites were randomly chosen along the reach using GIS and the Excel random number generator to determine a random distance upstream from a reach's lower end a site was to be located.

Plot baseline center was randomly chosen by walking along the bank upstream a distance determined by the "watch" technique- one observer looks at their watch and another observer says "stop" at an arbitrary time, the location of the second hand is the number chosen- to reduce and bias in selection of plot centerline. Plots were established on opposite banks in line perpendicular to stream bank.

Plots were 20x45 meters with the long axis perpendicular to the stream bank and with the edge of the plot aligned along the streambank. At the plot center along the stream bank, compass bearings of the stream bank were taken up and down stream and averaged, accounting for the 180 degree difference. The plot centerline bearing was established as the bearing perpendicular to the average stream bank bearing. Each plot was divided into 5 subplots extending away from the stream bank along the centerline bearing. Subplots included one 5x20 meter plot on the stream edge- at bankfull- and four 10x20 meter plots progressing away from the stream, numbered 1 through 5 progressing upslope.

methodStep.instrumentation: Measuring tape, 50 meters PVC posts to mark subplot boundaries along centerline

description.para: All trees in the plot greater than or equal to 5 inches diameter breast height (dbh) were identified to subplot location, species, measured for dbh, and put in a crown class. Height (estimated), dbh, and decay class of all snags greater than 5-inch dbh were recorded.
Heights of several trees in each crown class were measured with a laser rangefinder and recorded by tree number. Typically at least 10 trees were measured for height.
For further description of crown and decay classes, see column definitions under the Trees & Snags data table.

Low shrubs cover was measured along the centerline using the line-intercept method. The beginning and end distance of continuous interception by each shrub species along the fiberglass measuring tape used to mark the centerline was recorded.

Tall shrubs were any shrub greater than 6 feet in height. In the case of tall shrubs in a subplot, cover across a two-meter wide belt transect running down the subplot centerline was estimated for each subplot for that species. If there were multiple species greater than 6 feet in height, each species' cover was estimated separately for the two-meter wide belt.

Herb cover was measured within a 1 mÂ² quadrat in each subplot. The 1 mÂ² quadrat was located along the upstream side of the centerline in the middle of the subplot. The quadrat was framed on two sides by a 2-meter folding, wooden measuring ruler and one the third side by the centerline tape. The upslope edges of the quadrats were set at the 2.5, 10, 20, 30, and 40 meter marks on the centerline for subplots 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5 respectively.

Within each quadrat, the cover of all herb and fern species- including swordfern- was estimated by modified Daubenmire cover classes and recorded. In addition to herb cover, cover by moss, duff, wood greater than 5 inches in diameter, rock, mineral soil, and tree bole was estimated and recorded.

Saplings were defined as stems of tree species less than 5 inches in diameter breast height. Saplings were recorded by subplot, species, size class, and the substrate on which they were growing. The area sampled for saplings varied. In most plots, the whole plot was sampled, but if the number of saplings was particularly high, only the upstream half of the plot was sampled. In two old-growth plots (7 and 8), a smaller area for class 1 saplings was sampled because of the very high number of this size class. This smaller area consisted of a two-meter wide belt transect running down the center of the plot, perpendicular to the stream bank. Area sampled for each plot was noted to allow for scaling up to a standard subplot area.
Class 2: greater than 4.5 feet height and less than 3 inches diameter breast height
Class 3: greater than 4.5 feet height and between 3 and 5 inches diameter breast height
Substrate Class: mineral soil/duff, stumps, coarse woody debris greater than 5 inches in diameter

Canopy closure was measured in two locations in each plot, defined by the intersection of the centerline with the boundaries between subplots 2 and 3 and between subplots 4 and 5. Canopy closure was measured using a spherical densiometer following the standard protocol provided with the densiometer, with one exception: instead of facing north, east, south, and west while making the measurements, the observer faced in opposite directions along the centerline and along the perpendicular transect.

methodStep.instrumentation: Spherical densiometer, both convex and concave have been used

description.para: All herb and shrub species observed in the plot but not recorded in the shrub and herb sampling were recorded as other species. Although a reasonably thorough survey of each plot for additional species was made, some rare species of small stature may have been overlooked.

Photographs were not taken in 2003 but were in 2005 and in the 2012 resampling. Five photographs were taken, one for each subplot. For subplot #1, the photograph was taken from the stream channel toward the plot in line with the plot centerline. For subplots #2 through #5, the photographs were taken at the downslope side of the subplot along the centerline looking upslope.

attribute.attributeDefinition: Date of sampling.
Description of what is being sampled. Tree is a living, standing tree. Snag is a standing dead tree. Stumps are tree stumps.

All trees in the upstream half of the plot were tagged with numbered aluminum tags. If the number of trees in the upstream half was less than 25, trees in the downstream half were also tagged. During resampling in 2012, some of the trees had tags that were nailed to the tree without any room from growth. The tree bole growth over nine years enveloped the tags, making some hard to read and some not even evident. New tags were installed with the new numbers cross-referenced to the old where possible. New tags are listed after a semi-colon when the old number could be cross-referenced.

Species of the sampled specimen. Plant codes are used to identify tree species, using the standard convention of the first two letters of the genus followed by the first two letters of the specific epithet.
Diameter breast height, recorded in inches.
Percentage the tree crown comprises of the tree's total height. Methods unknown.
Tree height recorded in feet. Measurements were collected with a laser rangefinder. In some cases, especially in the case of snags, tree heights were estimated by sight.
Height from the base of the tree to the bottom of the crown in feet. Methods unknown.
Categorical description of sampled tree's crown.

codeDefinition.definition: Codominant. Trees with crowns forming the general level of the trees immediately around the measured trees. The crown is generally smaller than those of the dominant trees and is usually more crowded on the sides, receiving full light from above and little from the sides.

Intermediate: Trees with crowns below, but extending into, the general level of the trees immediately around the measured trees. The crowns are usually small and quite crowded on the sides, receiving little direct light from above but none from the sides.

Codominant. Trees with crowns forming the general level of the trees immediately around the measured trees. The crown is generally smaller than those of the dominant trees and is usually more crowded on the sides, receiving full light from above and little from the sides.

Dominant: Trees with crowns that extend above the general level of the trees immediately around the measured trees. They are somewhat taller than the codominant trees, and have well-developed crowns, which may be somewhat crowded on the sides, receiving full light from above and partly from the side.

Intermediate: Trees with crowns below, but extending into, the general level of the trees immediately around the measured trees. The crowns are usually small and quite crowded on the sides, receiving little direct light from above but none from the sides.

Intermediate: Trees with crowns below, but extending into, the general level of the trees immediately around the measured trees. The crowns are usually small and quite crowded on the sides, receiving little direct light from above but none from the sides.
Is: Isolated: Tree crowns receive full light from above and all sides. Usually the general level of the canopy is not evident.
Overtopped: Trees with crowns entirely below the general level of the trees around the measured trees, receiving no direct light either from above or from the sides.

attribute.attributeDefinition: Categorical description of sampled snag's level of decay.

codeDefinition.definition: Decay class 1: bark: tight, intact; limbs & branches: all present; top breakage: may be present; sapwood condition: sound, incipient decay, hark, original color; sapwood decay: none to incipient; heartwood condition: sound, hard, original color; bole form: intact

Decay class 2: bark: 50% loose or missing; limbs & branches: few limbs, no fine branches; top breakage: may be present; sapwood condition: advanced decay, fibrous, firm to soft, light brown; sapwood decay: none to incipient; heartwood condition: sound at base, incipient decay in outer edge of upper bole, hard, light to reddish brown; bole form: intact

Decay class 3: bark: 75% missing; limbs & branches: limbs stubs only; top breakage: ~1/3; sapwood condition: fibrous, soft, light to reddish brown; sapwood decay: none to 25%; heartwood condition: incipient decay at base, advanced decay throughout upper bole, fibbrous, hard to firm, reddish brown; bole form: mostly intact

Decay class 4: bark: 75% missing; limbs & branches: few or no stubs; top breakage: ~1/3-1/2; sapwood condition: cubical, soft reddish to dark brown; sapwood decay: 25%+; heartwood condition: advanced decay at base, sloughing from upper bole, fibrous to cubical, soft, dark reddish brown; bole form: losing form, soft

Decay class 5: bark: 75%+ missing; limbs & branches: none; top breakage: ~1/2+; sapwood condition: N/A; sapwood decay: 50%+ advanced; heartwood condition: sloughing, cubical, soft, dark brown or fibrous, very soft dark reddish brown, encased in hardened shell; bole form: form mostly lost

attribute.attributeDefinition: Tree age. Cores of at least two dominant trees in each subplots of 2 and 3 and subplots 4 and 5 were collected and stored temporarily in straws. Cores were subsequently mounted in grooved wooden blocks, sanded, and read to determine age. Although cores were taken during 2012 resampling, it was determine that collecting tree cores does not need to continue until the final sampling as those would be the most informative cores.

dataTable.entityDescription: Canopy closure measurements in the riparian permanent sample plots in the Cedar River Watershed, WA. Canopy closure was measured at two locations in each plot, defined by the intersection of the centerline with the boundaries between subplots 2 and 3 and between subplots 4 and 5. Canopy closure was measured with a spherical densiometer following the standard protocol provided with the densiometer, with one exception: instead of facing north, east, south, and west while making the measurements, the observer faced in opposite directions along the centerline and along the perpendicular transect. Measurements were taken with both a convex and concave densiometer and it is unknown which measurements used which tool. Counts of dots in open sky were made, but percent canopy closure was ultimately calculated. It is unknown for all observations which direction of the intersection was faced when collecting the count columns 1, 2, 3, and 4.

attribute.attributeDefinition: Plot number. Plots were 20x45 meters with the long axis perpendicular to the stream bank and with the edge of the plot aligned along the stream bank. Each plot was further divided into 5 subplots extending away from the bank.

Subplot number. Each plot was divided into 5 subplots extending away from the bank. Subplots included one 5x20 meter plot on the stream edge (i.e., at bankfull) and four 10x20 meter plots progressing away from the stream, numbered 1 through 5 progressing upslope. This sampling design was developed to allow analysis of gradients away from the stream channel and in relation to different fluvial geomorphic surfaces and associated disturbance regimes. Canopy closure measurements were taken at two intersections within each plot, at the centerline with boundaries between subplots 2 and 4 and between subplots 4 and 5.

dataTable.entityDescription: Herb and shrub species observed in the riparian permanent sample plots in the Cedar River Watershed, WA. Specifically, this table focuses on the herb and shrub species observed in the plot but not previously recorded in the shrub and herb sampling tables. Although a reasonably thorough survey of each plot for additional species was made, some rare species of small stature may have been overlooked.
